                "impact": "high",
                "recommendation": "## ISSUE EXPLANATION\n\nThis PDF lacks proper tagging structure, which means assistive technologies like screen readers cannot understand the document's logical reading order, headings, lists, or other structural elements. This violates Section 508 § 1194.22(i) requiring information to be organized so it's understandable when accessed through assistive technology, and WCAG 2.1 Success Criterion 1.3.1 (Info and Relationships) requiring structural markup to be programmatically determinable.\n\n## STEP-BY-STEP SOLUTION\n\n**Step 1:** Open the PDF in Adobe Acrobat Pro (not Reader)\n- Go to **File > Open** and select your valid.pdf file\n\n**Step 2:** Access the Accessibility Tools\n- Go to **Tools > Accessibility** in the top menu\n- Click **\"Full Check\"** to run a complete accessibility audit first\n\n**Step 3:** Add Tags to Document Structure\n- In the Accessibility panel, click **\"Add Tags to Document\"**\n- OR use the menu: **Tools > Accessibility > Add Tags to Document**\n- A dialog box will appear - click **\"OK\"** to proceed with automatic tagging\n\n**Step 4:** Review and Refine Tag Structure\n- Open the **Tags panel**: **View > Show/Hide > Navigation Panes > Tags** (F6)\n- The Tags panel will show the document's structure tree\n- Expand the tree to review heading levels, paragraphs, and lists\n\n**Step 5:** Fix Tag Order (if needed)\n- In the Tags panel, drag and drop elements to correct reading order\n- Right-click problematic tags and select **\"Properties\"** to change tag types\n- Ensure headings follow logical hierarchy (H1, H2, H3, etc.)\n\n## VERIFICATION STEPS\n\n**Step 1:** Run Accessibility Checker\n- Go to **Tools > Accessibility > Full Check**\n- Verify \"Document is tagged PDF\" shows as **\"Passed\"**\n\n**Step 2:** Test Reading Order\n- Go to **View > Show/Hide > Navigation Panes > Order**\n- Click **\"Show Order Panel\"** to verify logical reading sequence\n\n**Step 3:** Screen Reader Test\n- Use **Read Out Loud**: **View > Read Out Loud > Activate Read Out Loud** (Ctrl+Shift+Y)\n- Listen to ensure content flows logically\n\n## ADDITIONAL NOTES\n\n**Alternative Method:** If automatic tagging produces poor results, use **Tools > Accessibility > Reading Order Tool** for manual tag assignment. For complex documents, consider recreating from the source file (Word, InDesign) with proper accessibility features enabled before converting to PDF.",
                "remediation": "## ISSUE EXPLANATION\n\nThis PDF lacks proper tagging structure, which means assistive technologies like screen readers cannot understand the document's logical reading order, headings, lists, or other structural elements. This violates Section 508 § 1194.22(i) requiring information to be organized so it's understandable when accessed through assistive technology, and WCAG 2.1 Success Criterion 1.3.1 (Info and Relationships) requiring structural markup to be programmatically determinable.\n\n## STEP-BY-STEP SOLUTION\n\n**Step 1:** Open the PDF in Adobe Acrobat Pro (not Reader)\n- Go to **File > Open** and select your valid.pdf file\n\n**Step 2:** Access the Accessibility Tools\n- Go to **Tools > Accessibility** in the top menu\n- Click **\"Full Check\"** to run a complete accessibility audit first\n\n**Step 3:** Add Tags to Document Structure\n- In the Accessibility panel, click **\"Add Tags to Document\"**\n- OR use the menu: **Tools > Accessibility > Add Tags to Document**\n- A dialog box will appear - click **\"OK\"** to proceed with automatic tagging\n\n**Step 4:** Review and Refine Tag Structure\n- Open the **Tags panel**: **View > Show/Hide > Navigation Panes > Tags** (F6)\n- The Tags panel will show the document's structure tree\n- Expand the tree to review heading levels, paragraphs, and lists\n\n**Step 5:** Fix Tag Order (if needed)\n- In the Tags panel, drag and drop elements to correct reading order\n- Right-click problematic tags and select **\"Properties\"** to change tag types\n- Ensure headings follow logical hierarchy (H1, H2, H3, etc.)\n\n## VERIFICATION STEPS\n\n**Step 1:** Run Accessibility Checker\n- Go to **Tools > Accessibility > Full Check**\n- Verify \"Document is tagged PDF\" shows as **\"Passed\"**\n\n**Step 2:** Test Reading Order\n- Go to **View > Show/Hide > Navigation Panes > Order**\n- Click **\"Show Order Panel\"** to verify logical reading sequence\n\n**Step 3:** Screen Reader Test\n- Use **Read Out Loud**: **View > Read Out Loud > Activate Read Out Loud** (Ctrl+Shift+Y)\n- Listen to ensure content flows logically\n\n## ADDITIONAL NOTES\n\n**Alternative Method:** If automatic tagging produces poor results, use **Tools > Accessibility > Reading Order Tool** for manual tag assignment. For complex documents, consider recreating from the source file (Word, InDesign) with proper accessibility features enabled before converting to PDF.",
